english:
  title: A Letter to the Prime Ministers of This Realm
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow twice in reverence and submit this letter to Your Excellencies, the Prime Ministers.

    Though illness prevents me from presenting myself before you to speak my thoughts directly, I cannot remain silent. For if I do not voice what weighs upon my heart, not only will my mind fester with discontent, but you will surely dismiss me as a man of no understanding, unworthy of regard. Thus I dare break my silence, though I implore you to hear me with patience.

    Our three kingdoms have long ceased to be true kingdoms. Customs have crumbled, law and order lie in chaos, and the people suffer as though trapped in mud and ash. Yet Heaven has blessed us with a new sovereign and ministers who have received the mandate—the people look to you as they look to rain in times of drought.

    But if the sovereign and ministers, advancing in years, remain humble and silent, delegating all governance to you, then upon your shoulders fall the fate of the realm, the welfare of the people, and the rise and fall of worthy men. When worthy men flourish, the state endures; when they are dismissed, the people suffer. This is the eternal law of heaven and earth.

    Thus the selection of men is the very foundation of governance. Yet selecting men is easy, while knowing men is hard. When officials care not for virtue or corruption, rank or merit—viewing only wealth and bowing only to power—appointing flatterers while dismissing the honest, is this not the easiest path? And when selecting men becomes easy, governance descends into chaos, and chaos brings the state to ruin. We need not consult ancient history; this is plain before our eyes.

    The ancients understood this well. When appointing or dismissing officials, they carefully examined conduct and character, ever fearful of being corrupted by wealth or swayed by power. Yet even they sometimes confused jade with stone, crimson with purple.

    But in our realm, wealth is deemed ability, power is deemed wisdom. The robes of office and the caps of scholars have become costumes for jesters and charlatans. Straight speech and righteous counsel are mocked as the ravings of madmen. Is it any wonder the realm has fallen into ruin?

    This is why I have abandoned my family and homeland to dwell here near the capital—not for advancement, but because I could not bear to witness such degradation.

    Yet I hear that the reforms you undertake differ little from the old ways. In name you honor the aged, yet young men hold the reins. You claim to prize integrity, yet the greedy wield power. You have removed petty villains, yet greater evils remain unchanged. You have dismissed old ministers, yet new appointees merely cling to the old factions. If discerning men is not difficult and employing men is far too easy, then can this accord with the sovereign's true intentions? When the court hears of this, how can there be no cause for concern?

    Some say I should not write to you, lest I only provoke your anger to no avail. But I say: if the realm is secure and the people prosper, I shall lay out the full case before the court and present it to the Son of Heaven. Would I then remain silent merely because you are displeased? Therefore I humbly offer these words of one half-blind and wholly foolish, praying that you will deign to consider them.
  footnotes:
    - The 'three kingdoms' (三韓) refers to the ancient Korean kingdoms of Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla; here it refers poetically to Korea itself.
    - Lee Gok was a renowned Goryeo official and scholar (1298-1351) who was known for his moral courage in remonstrating with rulers and ministers.
